WEBVTT

00:00:01.440 --> 00:00:06.720
<v Speaker 1>I would like to talk a little bit more about writing in Spanish.

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:11.200
<v Speaker 1>So we haven't really looked so much about how to read and write in Spanish.

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:13.520
<v Speaker 1>We've spelled some words, we've discussed

00:00:13.740 --> 00:00:25.420
<v Speaker 1>some sounds and we've looked at convertible words convertible words that we convert over from Latin English into Spanish and they give us a great idea about

00:00:25.619 --> 00:00:28.820
<v Speaker 1>how to read and write in Spanish.

00:00:28.820 --> 00:00:36.820
<v Speaker 1>For example, if we have a just sound, now for example in general, how is this pronounced in Spanish?

00:00:38.140 --> 00:00:38.940
<v Speaker 1>General.

00:00:38.940 --> 00:00:40.460
<v Speaker 1>And it's spelt the same.

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:44.060
<v Speaker 1>So there we understand that G E makes sound.

00:00:44.060 --> 00:00:49.020
<v Speaker 1>Without having to learn it formally, we can just look back to these convertible words.

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:53.760
<v Speaker 1>when we are unsure of how a sound might be pronounced.

00:00:53.760 --> 00:00:58.240
<v Speaker 1>So maybe you see C E together and you're like, is that C or is that C?

00:00:58.520 --> 00:01:03.320
<v Speaker 1>But then if you look back to concentración, then you have your answer.

00:01:04.199 --> 00:01:08.520
<v Speaker 1>See, concentracion gives you your answer.

00:01:08.460 --> 00:01:17.020
<v Speaker 1>So apart from the actual sounds, we also need to understand where the stress in any given word is when we read it.

00:01:16.920 --> 00:01:24.040
<v Speaker 1>So in Spanish you may have noticed you have written accents, little dashes above some vowels

00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:30.840
<v Speaker 1>Now, this isn't like French, for example, where the little dashes might actually change the sound of the vowel.

00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:34.439
<v Speaker 1>None of that, luckily, is going on in Spanish.

00:01:34.420 --> 00:01:37.939
<v Speaker 1>The written accent is just showing the stress.

00:01:37.939 --> 00:01:41.940
<v Speaker 1>But why do we have it sometimes and not other times

00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:50.880
<v Speaker 1>So there is a general rule in Spanish, which is if the word ends in a vowel, an N or an S

00:01:51.820 --> 00:01:57.900
<v Speaker 1>The accent should be on the penultimate syllable, on the second last syllable.

00:01:57.900 --> 00:02:04.540
<v Speaker 1>Now why do you think vowels and then Ns and S's have been singled out for that rule

00:02:05.900 --> 00:02:08.140
<v Speaker 1>What if you look at our verbs?

00:02:08.140 --> 00:02:12.140
<v Speaker 1>What do our verb forms end in?

00:02:12.220 --> 00:02:15.180
<v Speaker 2>Well the the they end in an N.

00:02:15.180 --> 00:02:15.819
<v Speaker 1>Right

00:02:16.500 --> 00:02:18.500
<v Speaker 2>Ah yes, S as well.

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:19.380
<v Speaker 1>Or?

00:02:19.380 --> 00:02:20.180
<v Speaker 2>VAL.

00:02:20.180 --> 00:02:20.740
<v Speaker 1>Exactly.

00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:22.500
<v Speaker 1>So it's what our verbs end in.

00:02:22.500 --> 00:02:24.740
<v Speaker 1>In N, S or VAL.

00:02:24.560 --> 00:02:36.640
<v Speaker 1>So Spanish says if a word ends in NSO vowel, the natural accent will be on the penultimate syllable, the second last syllable, diferente, habla.

00:02:36.879 --> 00:02:38.239
<v Speaker 1>Ablan.

00:02:38.239 --> 00:02:39.439
<v Speaker 1>Ablas.

00:02:39.439 --> 00:02:40.799
<v Speaker 1>Ablamos.

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:45.040
<v Speaker 1>Ending S, but we're adding two syllables, so it's still on the second last.

00:02:45.040 --> 00:02:46.400
<v Speaker 1>Ablamos.

00:02:46.940 --> 00:02:48.700
<v Speaker 1>Importante.

00:02:48.700 --> 00:02:50.140
<v Speaker 1>Addictivo.

00:02:50.140 --> 00:02:55.420
<v Speaker 1>Now, if the word ends in any other consonant, any other consonant is not N-O-S

00:02:55.760 --> 00:03:03.600
<v Speaker 1>then the natural accent place is to go to the end of the word and we see this perfectly with any to verb.

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:04.080
<v Speaker 1>No?

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:06.240
<v Speaker 1>How do you say to eat?

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:08.540
<v Speaker 1>Accent on the end.

00:03:15.739 --> 00:03:18.220
<v Speaker 1>Ablar to find

00:03:20.520 --> 00:03:21.640
<v Speaker 1>Encontrar.

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:27.960
<v Speaker 1>So this R is not an N or an S or a vowel, and what that means is that the accent is coming on the end.

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:31.020
<v Speaker 1>So these are our natural accents.

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:37.980
<v Speaker 1>And if the word obeys the rules of the natural accents, we have no written accent generally.

00:03:37.980 --> 00:03:40.380
<v Speaker 1>There's a couple of exceptions which I will mention

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:43.400
<v Speaker 1>So if there's no written accent, you follow those rules.

00:03:43.400 --> 00:03:52.040
<v Speaker 1>If it ends NSO vowel, you put the accent on the second last syllable and if it ends in any other consonant, you're putting the accent on the end.

00:03:51.820 --> 00:04:00.220
<v Speaker 1>But if your word breaks this rule, then you have a written accent to show you where you should be stressing.

00:04:00.220 --> 00:04:03.980
<v Speaker 1>So for example, what is tradition in Spanish?

00:04:05.060 --> 00:04:06.100
<v Speaker 2>Tradición.

00:04:06.100 --> 00:04:07.140
<v Speaker 1>Tradición.

00:04:07.140 --> 00:04:09.780
<v Speaker 1>And what are you ending it with?

00:04:09.780 --> 00:04:11.860
<v Speaker 1>What is the last letter?

00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:13.319
<v Speaker 2>N.

00:04:13.319 --> 00:04:15.160
<v Speaker 1>And where is the accent?

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:16.359
<v Speaker 2>At the end.

00:04:16.359 --> 00:04:17.079
<v Speaker 1>At the end.

00:04:17.079 --> 00:04:18.760
<v Speaker 1>Does this break our rule?

00:04:18.760 --> 00:04:19.720
<v Speaker 2>Yes.

00:04:19.720 --> 00:04:21.000
<v Speaker 1>So the O

00:04:21.340 --> 00:04:27.420
<v Speaker 1>Will have a written accent that last O will have a written accent on the end showing you that you're stressing it.

00:04:29.420 --> 00:04:39.420
<v Speaker 1>So all of these yon words that all have their accent on the end, situation, opinion, they all have a written accent there on the end.

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:47.280
<v Speaker 1>So now I'm going to tell you some words that we've come across already, and I want you to tell me if they will have a written accent or not.

00:04:47.280 --> 00:04:52.800
<v Speaker 1>So what you need to decide is are they breaking the accent rule or not?

00:04:52.980 --> 00:04:54.580
<v Speaker 1>Encuentro.

00:04:54.580 --> 00:04:55.620
<v Speaker 1>Encuentro.

00:04:55.620 --> 00:04:56.980
<v Speaker 1>Firstly, what does that mean?

00:04:56.980 --> 00:04:58.900
<v Speaker 1>Encuentro.

00:04:58.900 --> 00:05:00.180
<v Speaker 2>I encounter.

00:05:00.180 --> 00:05:00.580
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:00.580 --> 00:05:01.700
<v Speaker 1>I find.

00:05:01.700 --> 00:05:02.660
<v Speaker 1>Encuentro.

00:05:02.660 --> 00:05:04.900
<v Speaker 1>Do we have a written accent there?

00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:06.259
<v Speaker 2>No.

00:05:06.259 --> 00:05:06.900
<v Speaker 1>No.

00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:07.860
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:07.860 --> 00:05:09.139
<v Speaker 1>Encontro.

00:05:09.139 --> 00:05:10.500
<v Speaker 1>What does that mean first?

00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:12.820
<v Speaker 1>Encontro?

00:05:12.900 --> 00:05:14.340
<v Speaker 2>I uh sorry

00:05:14.580 --> 00:05:19.780
<v Speaker 2>He she it or you formal found.

00:05:19.860 --> 00:05:20.340
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:20.340 --> 00:05:22.420
<v Speaker 1>And does it have a written accent

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:24.159
<v Speaker 2>Yes.

00:05:24.159 --> 00:05:25.759
<v Speaker 1>Yes, because it's breaking the rule.

00:05:25.759 --> 00:05:28.639
<v Speaker 1>We're ending in a vowel and we have the accent on the end.

00:05:28.639 --> 00:05:32.159
<v Speaker 1>So all of these in that point in the past are gonna have that accent.

00:05:32.159 --> 00:05:36.479
<v Speaker 1>Encontro ablo yamo yego.

00:05:36.479 --> 00:05:37.759
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:38.220
<v Speaker 1>Be there.

00:05:38.220 --> 00:05:38.780
<v Speaker 1>Be there.

00:05:38.780 --> 00:05:39.980
<v Speaker 1>Firstly, what does that mean?

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:41.820
<v Speaker 1>Be there?

00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:45.260
<v Speaker 2>He, she, it, you, former, live.

00:05:45.260 --> 00:05:45.740
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:45.740 --> 00:05:47.500
<v Speaker 1>Does it have an accent?

00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:49.200
<v Speaker 2>No.

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:50.000
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:51.920
<v Speaker 1>Vivio.

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:53.520
<v Speaker 2>It has an accent.

00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:54.240
<v Speaker 1>Where?

00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:55.200
<v Speaker 1>At the O.

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:55.680
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:55.680 --> 00:05:56.400
<v Speaker 1>Vivio

00:05:56.920 --> 00:06:00.680
<v Speaker 1>He lived, she lived, Euphumu lived, it lived.

00:06:00.680 --> 00:06:04.040
<v Speaker 1>Limon, what do you think limon means?

00:06:04.040 --> 00:06:04.760
<v Speaker 2>Lemon?

00:06:04.760 --> 00:06:05.880
<v Speaker 1>Lemon, good.

00:06:05.880 --> 00:06:09.800
<v Speaker 1>Which is a Persian word actually and and it actually was used

00:06:09.960 --> 00:06:21.960
<v Speaker 1>to talk about citrus fruits uh generically generally and lime came from the same word so lemon and lime is actually the same word essentially does it have an accent limon

00:06:23.320 --> 00:06:24.040
<v Speaker 2>Yes.

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:26.360
<v Speaker 1>Yes, because it should be limon, right?

00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:28.040
<v Speaker 1>But it's not, it's limon.

00:06:28.040 --> 00:06:31.240
<v Speaker 1>It's breaking that rule, so it has a written accent

00:06:31.420 --> 00:06:41.980
<v Speaker 1>So when we're reading Spanish, if the word ends in a vowel, an N or an S, we want to put the accent on the penultimate syllable.

00:06:41.660 --> 00:06:52.220
<v Speaker 1>If it ends in another consonant, we want to put the accent on the end unless we are shown with a written accent that the rule is being broken.

00:06:52.540 --> 00:06:58.220
<v Speaker 1>Salud means health related to salut in English.

00:06:58.220 --> 00:07:01.100
<v Speaker 1>Salud and you can say it when you toast.

00:07:01.100 --> 00:07:03.259
<v Speaker 1>Does it have a written accent?

00:07:03.660 --> 00:07:04.380
<v Speaker 2>No.

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:04.860
<v Speaker 1>No.

00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:05.260
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:07:05.260 --> 00:07:09.820
<v Speaker 1>It ends in a D, so we expect the accent to be on the end.

00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:10.780
<v Speaker 1>Salute.

00:07:10.780 --> 00:07:15.420
<v Speaker 1>So usually accents are written to show us that we're breaking the accent rule.

00:07:15.420 --> 00:07:16.620
<v Speaker 1>But there are some other

00:07:16.860 --> 00:07:19.340
<v Speaker 1>situations where we have a written accent.

00:07:19.340 --> 00:07:29.980
<v Speaker 1>One of these situations is when we have words that are monosyllables, words that are just one syllable, and we can differentiate them with a written accent

00:07:29.840 --> 00:07:33.280
<v Speaker 1>For example, how was the word for yes?

00:07:33.280 --> 00:07:33.920
<v Speaker 1>C.

00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:36.160
<v Speaker 1>And how was the word for if?

00:07:36.160 --> 00:07:36.800
<v Speaker 2>C.

00:07:36.800 --> 00:07:37.200
<v Speaker 1>C.

00:07:37.200 --> 00:07:38.320
<v Speaker 1>It's the same word.

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:41.120
<v Speaker 1>So yes is written with a written accent.

00:07:40.940 --> 00:07:42.300
<v Speaker 1>And if is not.

00:07:42.300 --> 00:07:45.500
<v Speaker 1>Now this written accent doesn't change the pronunciation.

00:07:45.500 --> 00:07:53.340
<v Speaker 1>This differentiates them so when you're reading, you don't have the ambiguity that could sometimes be caused by, oh, is that an yes or an if

00:07:53.440 --> 00:08:00.080
<v Speaker 1>Both could make sense there, especially because you use yes emphatically in Spanish because I see lo quiero.

00:08:00.080 --> 00:08:01.600
<v Speaker 1>Yes, I want it.

00:08:01.520 --> 00:08:08.800
<v Speaker 1>But if that's written and you don't hear the emphasis, silo quiero, then you might read if I want it.

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:12.400
<v Speaker 1>So to clear up that ambiguity when you have monosyllables

00:08:12.560 --> 00:08:17.600
<v Speaker 1>words of one syllable that are the same, one will take an accent to show the difference.

00:08:17.600 --> 00:08:20.400
<v Speaker 1>How was for me?

00:08:20.400 --> 00:08:22.560
<v Speaker 2>Para me or for me.

00:08:22.560 --> 00:08:23.040
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:23.600
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:26.320
<v Speaker 1>Either one, depending what for you want.

00:08:26.139 --> 00:08:28.780
<v Speaker 1>Now how was my house?

00:08:28.780 --> 00:08:29.740
<v Speaker 1>Mikasa.

00:08:29.740 --> 00:08:31.020
<v Speaker 1>Mikasa.

00:08:31.020 --> 00:08:33.180
<v Speaker 1>So this is different me

00:08:33.860 --> 00:08:39.700
<v Speaker 1>One is the the me that comes after prepossessions, parami, por mi, demi.

00:08:39.700 --> 00:08:42.580
<v Speaker 1>And the other one is for possession, my.

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:42.900
<v Speaker 1>So

00:08:43.339 --> 00:08:49.980
<v Speaker 1>Parami, there you have the written accent on the mi of parami and you don't have it on mi kasa.

00:08:49.980 --> 00:08:51.660
<v Speaker 1>Just to show the difference.

00:08:51.660 --> 00:08:55.500
<v Speaker 1>What was the word for you speaking informally?

00:08:55.779 --> 00:08:56.420
<v Speaker 1>Tu.

00:08:56.420 --> 00:08:56.820
<v Speaker 1>Tu.

00:08:56.820 --> 00:08:58.740
<v Speaker 1>And what was your house?

00:08:59.060 --> 00:09:00.260
<v Speaker 1>Tukasa.

00:09:00.260 --> 00:09:01.459
<v Speaker 1>Tukasa.

00:09:01.459 --> 00:09:04.980
<v Speaker 1>The word for you, tu takes a written accent.

00:09:04.720 --> 00:09:08.560
<v Speaker 1>But the word for you're in your house, tukasa, doesn't.

00:09:08.560 --> 00:09:13.200
<v Speaker 1>So monosyllables that are the same are differentiated by accent.

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:15.680
<v Speaker 1>I know, how do you say I know?

00:09:16.040 --> 00:09:19.720
<v Speaker 1>Se yes this se has a written accent.

00:09:19.720 --> 00:09:23.400
<v Speaker 1>The se of se lodoi, I give it to him

00:09:23.459 --> 00:09:29.060
<v Speaker 1>The se of se queda, he remains himself, she remains herself, doesn't have an accent.

00:09:29.060 --> 00:09:32.899
<v Speaker 1>Only the se of saber, I know, has one.

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:35.700
<v Speaker 1>So it's something you will pick up reading.

00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:44.660
<v Speaker 1>Another example where we have accents is to differentiate question words from non-question words when they're the same.

00:09:44.660 --> 00:09:46.180
<v Speaker 1>For example,

00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:47.760
<v Speaker 1>You have donde.

00:09:47.760 --> 00:09:49.840
<v Speaker 1>What does donde mean?

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:50.640
<v Speaker 2>Where?

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:51.440
<v Speaker 1>Where?

00:09:51.440 --> 00:09:56.160
<v Speaker 1>But sometimes donde is a question word, like donde stas.

00:09:56.160 --> 00:09:57.360
<v Speaker 1>Where are you?

00:09:57.360 --> 00:09:59.360
<v Speaker 1>There it will go with an accent

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:07.280
<v Speaker 1>But if I say I'm going to meet him where we saw the football, this is not a question

00:10:07.259 --> 00:10:08.699
<v Speaker 1>So it doesn't have an accent.

00:10:08.699 --> 00:10:11.180
<v Speaker 1>So Spanish likes to differentiate them as well.

00:10:11.180 --> 00:10:19.660
<v Speaker 1>But now we're entering in quite a bit of detail and many Spanish speakers when they're writing make these mistakes as well and don't put these accents where they should

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:27.459
<v Speaker 1>But I'm explaining just in case you come across Don Day with an accent and you don't understand why it's there because it's not breaking the accent rule.

00:10:27.459 --> 00:10:28.580
<v Speaker 1>This is why

00:10:28.459 --> 00:10:38.540
<v Speaker 1>So in the same way we have commo which means how or like the commo for how takes an accent and the commo for like doesn't

00:10:38.820 --> 00:10:49.380
<v Speaker 1>So there are a couple of grammatical examples when we are having accents just to differentiate words that are the same or to differentiate question words from non-question words.

00:10:49.040 --> 00:10:54.240
<v Speaker 1>But most of the time they are directing us to break the accenting rules.

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:58.480
<v Speaker 1>And it's very easy to remember the accenting rules because

00:10:58.820 --> 00:11:01.540
<v Speaker 1>We only need to look at the present tense.

00:11:01.540 --> 00:11:10.340
<v Speaker 1>We know that our verbs end in vowels and s and in the present tense we always have the accent on the penultimate syllable.

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:12.160
<v Speaker 1>without any written accent.

00:11:12.160 --> 00:11:21.440
<v Speaker 1>We have of course that one exception, a star, where we have estas, estan, sta, and we do have a written accent.

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:35.040
<v Speaker 1>So we can look back there at the present tense to remind us that if the word ends n, s or vowel, the natural accent is on the penultimate syllable like the verbs in the present tense.

00:11:34.540 --> 00:11:39.580
<v Speaker 1>and if it ends in any other letter, the natural accent is on the end of the word.

00:11:39.580 --> 00:11:43.019
<v Speaker 3>And if we break this rule, we show it with a written accent.

